abstract: A close call over the nomination of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives director could have unraveled a delicate truce between the two parties.
snippet: A close call over the nomination of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives director could have unraveled a delicate truce between the two parties.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — With the help of a last-minute switch from a “no” to a “yes,” Senate Democrats on Wednesday narrowly overcame a Republican filibuster of President Obama’s nominee to lead the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives — a close call that could have unraveled a delicate truce between the two parties.

abstract: But to some policy makers practiced in the art of compromise, preserving the power of the filibuster represented a potential missed opportunity.
snippet: But to some policy makers practiced in the art of compromise, preserving the power of the filibuster represented a potential missed opportunity.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate agreement to pull back from unilateral rules changes that would have eroded the power of the filibuster was hailed by both parties as the beginning of a new spirit of bipartisan cooperation that saved the Senate. But to some policy makers practiced in the art of compromise, it represented a potential missed opportunity.

lead_paragraph: There is renewed attention on Congressional dysfunction this week as the momentum slows on immigration reform and Republicans continue mounting their opposition to the new health care law. abstract: Senator Kirsten E. Gillibrand is leading a bipartisan group of women in a fierce battle to change attitudes about sexual crimes in the military and the legal system used to address them.
snippet: Senator Kirsten E. Gillibrand is leading a bipartisan group of women in a fierce battle to change attitudes about sexual crimes in the military and the legal system used to address them.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Shocking the gridlocked Congress into action, a half dozen or so bipartisan female senators are escalating their war on sexual crimes in the military and deploying their outrage, clout and legions of supporters against a rigid military structure and its male-dominated ranks.

abstract: Emily's List, one of the largest political action committees in the United States, is working to put the first woman in the White House.
snippet: Emily's List, one of the largest political action committees in the United States, is working to put the first woman in the White House.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Momentum to elect more women to high office, specifically to break the ultimate glass ceiling and elect a woman as president in the United States, has gone into high gear here with Emily’s List’s Madam President campaign, a fund-raising drive that in just a few weeks has gained thousands of new followers and thousands of dollars in donations.

abstract: President Obama’s choice to be transportation secretary, Mayor Anthony Foxx of Charlotte, N.C., zipped through a confirmation hearing on Wednesday before the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
snippet: President Obama’s choice to be transportation secretary, Mayor Anthony Foxx of Charlotte, N.C., zipped through a confirmation hearing on Wednesday before the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
lead_paragraph: President Obama’s choice to be transportation secretary, Mayor Anthony Foxx of Charlotte, N.C., zipped through a confirmation hearing on Wednesday before the Senate Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee. He was questioned on many points but pushed to make promises on nothing more than working cooperatively with Congress, putting safety first, trying to maintain air traffic control tower staffing, and visiting the site of the recent commuter train accident in Bridgeport, Conn.

abstract: Senator Kirsten Gillibrand will introduce a bill that would give military prosecutors rather than commanders the power to decide which sexual assault cases to try.
snippet: Senator Kirsten Gillibrand will introduce a bill that would give military prosecutors rather than commanders the power to decide which sexual assault cases to try.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Obama, military officials and lawmakers on Capitol Hill are in broad agreement that the sexual assault problem in the military has reached a level of severity that can no longer be tolerated. But that is far different from concurring on how it should be fixed.

abstract: More than a dozen members of Congress, mostly women from the Senate and House Armed Services Committees, met with Valerie Jarrett, a senior adviser to Mr. Obama.
snippet: More than a dozen members of Congress, mostly women from the Senate and House Armed Services Committees, met with Valerie Jarrett, a senior adviser to Mr. Obama.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In a sign that the White House is increasing its focus on the problem of sexual assault in the military, one of President Obama’s closest advisers met with a group of Congressional lawmakers on Thursday morning to discuss their legislative strategy for addressing the issue.
